^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|First, the auction. Let's discuss Nada's negative double. Given her heart length and spade shortness it was a good bid. It has been suggested that I should cue bid 2D (limit raise) rather than bid 2S. However, I have 2 problems with that.|
PG| ***** 42 ***** |


NT|^B@2
1) Most importantly, I don't have enough points. Playing Bergen, you could say I have 10 dummy points (8 HCP, 1 for doubleton, 1 for 5 card suit). But my diamond length is probably not that useful given West opened 1D
2) I like to make the cue bid with 4-card support. Sometimes I am stuck and have to cue with 3-card support. But I think discovering the 9th trump is very important, so my agreement is that cue bids promise 4-card support 90% of the time.|
PG| ***** 43 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|That is similar to the auction 1C-P-1S-P-2S, where 2S promises 4 but will be done on 3 on occasion. Now, when it goes P-P, Nada has a problem. One thing to note is, when the opponents have found a fit, and the points are evenly distributed, and they stop at the 2 level you should rarely pass. Letting them play at the 2 level when a suit has been bid and raised will more often than not be a bad result for your side.|
PG| ***** 44 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, although Nada only has 4 HCP, because of her heart length and spade shortness, she should bid 3H. In general, the person short in the opponents trump suit should be the one to bid. Nada had the opportunity to bid 2H and did not. So, if she then bids 3H after making a negative double, she is showing a hand with long hearts but not good enough to bid 2H. To repeat, if partner makes a "negative double and correct", so to speak, that shows a weak hand and a long suit because with a stronger hand partner would have bid the suit directly.|
PG| ***** 45 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Next, let's get to whether hope should bid 3H. That is a weak jump shift, and is certainly plausible. However, believe it or not her hand might be too strong to make a weak jump shift. If West has 4 hearts and a reasonable hand, you might want to play in game. But 3H is pretty much a shutout bid. West should not raise to 4 unless he has a really good hand, even with 4-card support.|
