NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One other point which is Roberta's 3S bid. Given Stan was a passed hand, it has some merit However, if Stan was not a passed hand, Roberta should strongly consider reopening with a double. If Stan had a penalty double, he can't make it, since a double there by Stan is negative. So, Roberta has to protect against a potential penalty double by Stan. Any time the bidding goes 1X-3Y-p-p, and you are short in suit Y (the preempter's suit) you should reopen with a double to protect if partner has a penalty double. Otherwise you will never be able to penalize the opponents. |
PG| ***** 238 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If Stan had not been a passed hand, then I think double by Roberta is better than bidding 3S. Although because she has such a good spade suit, 3S is still ok. But remember, you should strain to double in pass out seat if you are short in the overcaller's suit. |
PG| ***** 239 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If you are deciding whether or not to double for penalty (or convert pard's takeout double for penalty) the 2 most important factors are shortness in pard's suit (singleton or void), and length in trumps. If you have both of those, pass is almost always right. Shortness in pard's suit, plus trump control in their suit is golden on defense.|
